The rate is currently almost at zero. It is very unlikely that the Fed will go into negative interest rate territory to stimulate the economy. However, the second-quarter numbers will be in on growth and unemployment so a later June date is more likely to be a change downward than the June 20 date. The economic outlook will be very bleak on Jun 29.

Markets give the FED a 100% chance of sticking with the rates. This seems most realistic given the options: • Raise rates: Seems impossible to do for Powell given following reasons: o Economic forecasts for FY2020. Current earnings season proves the point o Next rate meeting would be in the middle of next earnings season, it might well be that the US is then tentatively more open and feeling the worst is behind them. So outlook might be better. Yet, according to most recent IMF estimate the US economy will still be severely hit. • Lower rates: o Lower rates would imply one of two things:  A downward shift of upper and lower band. This would imply negative rates, which hurt European banks in recent years and even prompted hikes in Scandinavia, the US is very unlikely to follow the EU in this regard • A single rate (upper band = lower band): o The FED did historically have a single rate which at current effective funds rate levels would mean a lower upper band o As of today, I see no indications anyone is discussing this

Prior to setting the target range in 2008, the target rate dropped sharply in response to the economic crisis that had just occurred. Similarly, the Fed recently dropped the range from 1.5%-1.75% to 1%-1.25% to 0%-0.25% in response to the economic crisis caused by the COVID-19 pandemic. Following the 2008 recession, the target range remained at the same rates for the following eight years. In 2016, the Fed raised the range from 0%-0.25% to 1%-1.25% as the US economy began recovering. Using this example, it is unlikely that the Fed will raise or lower their target range in the period between June and July 2020.
